        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <details>
            <summary>What are considered cheap AI stocks?</summary>
            <p>Cheap AI stocks are typically those trading at lower price-to-earnings (P/E) multiples compared to the broader high-growth tech sector, often found in legacy enterprise tech, semiconductor manufacturing equipment, or data center infrastructure.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary>Are cheap AI stocks a value trap?</summary>
            <p>They absolutely can be. It is crucial to fundamentally analyze whether the low valuation is due to structural business decline and obsolescence, or merely temporary market pessimism regarding their ability to transition to an AI-first model.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary>How do I evaluate an AI stock?</summary>
            <p>Look deeply at their specific AI monetization strategy, accelerating revenue growth, robust free cash flow, proprietary datasets, and how their valuation multiples compare historically and relative to their direct competitors.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary>Should I buy AI stocks or an AI ETF?</summary>
            <p>ETFs offer broad exposure and significantly lower risk through diversification, while individual stocks offer much higher potential alpha but come with devastatingly higher volatility and company-specific execution risk.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary>What is the best way to invest in AI?</summary>
            <p>A prudently balanced approach often involves holding a core, low-cost broad technology ETF and supplementing it with carefully selected, deeply researched, undervalued individual AI stocks to capture specialized growth.</p>
        </details>

